id: pm-8kch
title: pm deps context format reports missing_count without enumerating missing references and disagrees with tree format
description: "pm deps --format context returns a top-level missing_count scalar (3 on pm-96h7) but the payload contains no list of which references are missing or which neighbor declares them; pm deps --format tree on the same item reports missing_count 0. Agents cannot distinguish ignorable legacy ghosts on closed neighbors from repairable typos on active items, and the two formats contradict each other."
type: Issue
status: closed
priority: 2
tags[5]: agent-ux,"area:cli",contracts,graph,sdk
created_at: "2026-07-16T05:50:30.876Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-17T06:47:05.279Z"
closed_at: "2026-07-17T06:27:06.943Z"
author: maintainer-agent
estimated_minutes: 120
acceptance_criteria: "context and tree formats agree on missing_count semantics for the same item and depth, or the difference is explicitly documented in the payload; the context payload enumerates missing references with the declaring node id, the dangling target id, and edge kind, bounded by the existing node/edge limits; missing references are classified active vs legacy-terminal following the pm-2ler split so agents know what is repairable; JSON and TOON shapes stay in sync with cli-contracts and the MCP schema; covering spec added"
parent: pm-96h7
risk: low
confidence: high
resolution: fixed
expected_result: "Tree and context formats report the same traversal-scoped missing nodes, while context enumerates bounded declaring references and classifies active versus terminal-history debt across JSON, TOON, CLI, SDK, and MCP surfaces."
actual_result: "Context and tree now use traversal-scoped missing semantics; context enumerates bounded holder/target/kind/source/status rows with legacy-terminal classification, sentinel exclusion, and SDK/CLI/MCP/contract parity."
